<PageLayout
  title="Editorial standards"
  kicker="About"
  description="Accuracy, honesty, and traceable sources are the whole point of the project. Here is exactly how pages are written, sourced, reviewed, and corrected."
>
  <p>
    melanocortin.com is an open, educational reference on the melanocortin
    system — the POMC-derived peptides, the MC1R–MC5R receptors, and the
    therapeutics that target them. It is written to serve three audiences on the
    same pages: students and researchers who need mechanism and citations;
    clinicians and curious readers who want an accurate plain-language picture;
    and anyone arriving from a search engine who deserves a credible answer
    rather than a content farm.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because much of this material is health-related, the standard we hold
    ourselves to is higher than "sounds right." Every substantive claim should be
    traceable to a primary source, uncertainty should be stated rather than
    hidden, and the writing should never sell you anything. This page explains how
    we try to live up to that.
  </p>

  <h2>Who writes and edits this</h2>
  <p>
    Pages are researched, written, and maintained by the melanocortin.com
    editorial team. We write from the primary literature and regulatory
    documents — not by paraphrasing other secondary sites — and we do not use
    invented credentials or fictional "medical reviewers" to borrow authority we
    haven't earned.
  </p>
  <p>
    We are formalising named authorship and independent expert review. Until a
    qualified reviewer has actually signed off on a page, that page is dated
    <strong>"Last updated,"</strong> not "Last reviewed" — the two are different
    claims, and we will not blur them. When named, credentialed review is in
    place, it will appear on the page and be described here.
  </p>

  <h2>How we source claims</h2>
  <p>
    Claims of fact link to a shared, citeable source registry so you can check the
    original rather than take our word for it. In rough order of preference, we
    rely on:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Peer-reviewed primary literature and authoritative reviews</strong>
      — accessed through PubMed / PMC, and cited with PMIDs or DOIs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Regulatory documents</strong> — FDA approvals and prescribing
      information (via DailyMed), and equivalent agency records, for anything
      about what a drug is approved to do.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Primary company disclosures</strong> — trial results and filings,
      used carefully and labelled as the interested-party sources they are.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    We prefer the strongest available evidence, name the source in the text where
    it matters, and treat press releases and marketing as claims to verify, not
    facts to repeat.
  </p>

  <h2>How pages are reviewed and kept current</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Every page carries a visible byline and a dated last-update.</li>
    <li>
      Therapeutic and clinical-pipeline information dates quickly, so it is
      verified against current primary sources before publication and revisited
      as the field moves.
    </li>
    <li>
      Dates are shown to the year. We would rather commit to an honest
      "reviewed this year" than imply a false-precision timestamp we can't stand
      behind.
    </li>
    <li>
      Where the science is uncertain, contested, or genuinely unknown, the page
      says so — plainly — rather than papering over it.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Independence and funding</h2>
  <p>
    melanocortin.com is editorially independent. It is not sponsored by, and does
    not take payment from, any pharmaceutical company, compounder, or vendor to
    cover, favour, downplay, or omit a drug or product. What appears here is
    driven by what is scientifically and practically true, not by who might pay
    for coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the site ever introduces affiliate links or other commercial
    relationships, they will be <strong>clearly disclosed on the pages where they
    appear</strong>, they will not influence what we say about a product, and
    they will never turn an educational page into a sales pitch. Our bias is
    stated up front and it is a simple one: toward the reader.
  </p>

  <h2>Not medical advice</h2>
  <p>
    Content is for education and general information only. It is not medical
    advice, diagnosis, or treatment, and it is no substitute for a qualified
    clinician. We do not provide dosing, sourcing, or usage instructions for any
    drug, approved or otherwise. Never disregard professional medical advice, or
    delay seeking it, because of something you read here.
  </p>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>
    Found an error or an out-of-date claim? Corrections are welcome and credited.
    The fastest way to reach us is to
    <a href="https://github.com/utilityincoming/melanocortin/issues">open an issue
    on GitHub</a>, where changes are tracked in the open. We treat a well-sourced
    correction as a gift, not a nuisance — flagging a mistake makes the reference
    better for everyone who reads it next.
  </p>

  <h2>Licensing</h2>
